<DOC><DOCNO> AP891213-0295 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 2329EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-Boeing-Bonuses     12-13 0286</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Boeing-Bonuses,0300</SECOND><HEAD>Boeing To Pay $500 Million In Bonuses To Workers</HEAD><DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Boeing Co. will pay $500 million in bonusesthis month to its employees worldwide, including non-union workers,the company said Wednesday.   Of that amount, $374 million will go to nearly 107,000 employeesin Washington state, including more than 35,000 non-union workersin the Seattle area.   Both union and non-union workers will receive bonuses of 10percent, the company said.   Boeing, the Northwest's largest private employer, said earlierit would give office workers, administrators and supervisorsbonuses, but did not give a percentage until Wednesday.   Office workers have received bonuses annually, but professionalsand administrators last got bonuses three years ago, said PaulBinder, company spokesman.   The 43,000 members of the International Association ofMachinists andamp; Aerospace Workers in the state got 10 percent bonuseslast Friday, averaging more than $3,000 each.   Under their contract ratified Nov. 20 after a 48-day strike,they will get bonuses of 5 percent next year and 4 percent in 1991.   If about 28,000 members of the Seattle Professional EngineeringEmployees Association approve a contract offer, they will receive10 percent bonuses Dec. 22. The engineers and technical workershave until Dec. 18 to vote on the tentative contract.   The proposed offer calls for engineers to get a bonus this yearonly, but technical workers would get a 5 percent bonus next yearand 4 percent the following year.   Engineers would get an average bonus of nearly $4,000 whiletechnical workers would receive nearly $3,000.   The 1989 bonuses will also be distributed in four other areaswith major Boeing operations: Wichita, Kan., $72 million;Philadelphia, $18.5 million; Portland, Ore., $7 million; andHuntsville, Ala., $7 million.</TEXT></DOC>